            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": ">  ...new code developed for nvim has been submitted under the Apache license.\n\n> I vaguely recall questioning unibilium's license years ago, and IIRC @tarruda said the author was OK with our inclusion of it.\n\nThe easiest path forward is probably just relicensing historical pre-fork code. \n\n[There are only 5 contributors to the original code before the fork](https://github.com/mauke/unibilium/graphs/contributors). Those are the only people who need to consent, since all new code is already Apache licensed, from what it sounds like. But even if the new post-fork code also needs to relicense, [there are only 14 contributors post-fork](https://github.com/neovim/unibilium/graphs/contributors).\n\nFor context: in a different project I contributed to years ago, [they chose to relicense](https://github.com/racket/racket/issues/1570) and just replying to a Github issue with a templated affirmation was considered sufficient. That had hundreds of contributors and still succeeded in relicensing. Should be possible here with the much smaller number of contributors, and easier than replacing a core dependency.\n\nAlthough it sounds like [there is a plan to move to a different toolkit (?)](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/21832#discussion_r1071143289), asking permission to relicense is still probably a faster way forward for the time being until that happens.",
